[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[PlyCount "30"]
[EventDate "2021.??.??"]

1. e4 e5 2. f4 {Nowadays this move is considered dubious but still interesting.
} exf4 3. Nf3 (3. Bc4 $2 {Way too romantic for our time!} d5 $5 (3... Qh4+ $5
4. Kf1 d6 5. Nf3 (5. Nc3 Be6 $1 6. Bxe6 (6. Nf3 Bxc4+ $17) 6... fxe6 7. Nf3 Qh5
$17) 5... Qh6 $5 6. d4 Be6 $1 7. d5 Bg4 $17) 4. exd5 (4. Bxd5 Qh4+ 5. Kf1 Nf6
6. Nf3 Qh6 $1 7. Nc3 Bb4 8. Bb3 Nc6 9. d4 Bg4 $15) 4... Qh4+ 5. Kf1 Bd6 $1 6.
Nf3 (6. Qe1+ Qxe1+ 7. Kxe1 Nf6 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Nb5 Nbd7 $17 10. Nxd6 cxd6 11. Nf3
Nb6 $17) 6... Qh5 7. Nc3 Ne7 8. d4 O-O 9. Kf2 Bg4 10. h3 Bf5 $1 $17) 3... Ne7
$1 {There are several ways for Black to play in this position. We avoid
memorizing lines with 3... g5 or h6 and d6 because we don't want to play
White's game and go for the complicated kind of position that White wants to
achieve. The real problem when we play against the King's gambit is not to
find a good, valid line against it but to find practically good lines against
it. 3...Ne7 is a very interesting idea that I consider easy to learn. In
almost every case Black's move will be d5 (except for 4.Qe2-Nc6!) and then,
one way or another, he gains the d5 square for his knight. Black is never
interested in keeping his extra f4 pawn by playing moves like g7-g5. He just
wants to develop fast and get at least an equal game! White's most challenging
set-up is with 4.Qe2!? intending to go for long castling. But we have the
great plan with Nc6!, Bb4, Nce7!!, Bxc3 and then d7-d5!} 4. Bc4 $6 (4. Qe2 $1 {
A very interesting and tricky line for White. He is stopping our d5 idea and
he wants to develop and play 0-0-0, and continue his game with an attack. This
plan won't work well if we know what to do.} Ng6 $1 5. Nc3 $1 $132 {White
intends to go b3, Bb2, 0-0-0 and then attack with h4 or g3. Therefore, we need
to come up with a good plan for Black -> Nc6, Bb4, Nce7, Bxc3, and d7-d5!} (5.
d4 $2 {Pay attention to Black's amazing response here.} c5 $3 $15 {With the
idea of taking on d4 and playing Nc6.} 6. d5 (6. c3 {Now it is getting more
difficult for White to castle long side.} Be7 $1 $17 (6... d5 $17 7. exd5+ Be7
8. dxc5 Qxd5 $19) 7. g3 cxd4 8. cxd4 d5 9. exd5 O-O $19) 6... d6 7. h4 h5 $17 {
[%cal Yf8e7,Ye7f6,Yc8g4]}) (5. h4 $6 h5 $17 {The common responce.}) 5... Nc6 $3
{The best move in this position.} 6. d4 (6. h4 $6 h5 7. d4 Bb4 8. Bd2 Nce7 9.
a3 (9. O-O-O Bxc3 $1 10. Bxc3 d5 11. exd5 O-O $17 12. Ne5 Nf5 $3 $15) 9... Bxc3
10. Bxc3 d5 $17) (6. b3 $2 Bc5 $3 {[%cal Yc6d4] Preventing d4 and a knight is
coming there.} 7. Bb2 (7. Nd5 Nd4 8. Nxd4 Bxd4 9. c3 Qh4+ 10. Kd1 Bb6 $17 11.
d4 c6 12. Nxb6 axb6 $17) 7... Nd4 8. Qd3 Nxf3+ 9. Qxf3 Bd4 10. O-O-O d6 $17 11.
Kb1 Be6 $1 $17) 6... Bb4 $1 7. Bd2 Nce7 $3 {[%cal Yb4c3,Yd7d5] A very
important idea that you must remember!} 8. O-O-O $6 (8. d5 $5 O-O 9. O-O-O d6
10. a3 (10. g3 Bg4 11. gxf4 (11. h3 Bxf3 12. Qxf3 fxg3 13. Qxg3 f5 $3 $17)
11... Bxc3 12. Bxc3 Nxf4 13. Qf2 Neg6 $17 14. Rg1 Qd7 $15) (10. h4 h5 11. Nh2
Ne5 $1 12. Qxh5 N7g6 13. Qe2 Qxh4 $17) 10... Ba5 11. h4 h5 12. Nh2 Ne5 13. Qxh5
N7g6 $15) 8... Bxc3 $1 9. Bxc3 d5 $17 10. exd5 O-O $17) (4. d4 {Probably the
most common move.} d5 5. exd5 $6 (5. Bd3 $1 {this is the best move for White
here !} dxe4 6. Bxe4 Ng6 $1 $132 {This is one of the rare occasions when we
don't play Nd5 because here it is not working.} 7. Qe2 (7. h4 Bd6 $5 8. h5 Ne7
9. h6 g6 10. c4 c6 $15) 7... Be7 8. h4 O-O {The safe way to play. Nxh4 is also
an option but it is more risky.} 9. h5 Nh4 10. Bxf4 Nxf3+ 11. Qxf3 (11. gxf3
Nc6 12. c3 Bd6 $132) 11... Nd7 {[%cal Yd7f6]} 12. Nc3 Nf6 13. h6 g6 14. Qd3
Nxe4 (14... Bg4 $132) 15. Nxe4 Bf5 $132) (5. Nc3 dxe4 6. Nxe4 Nd5 {[%cal Yf8e7,
Ye8g8] The goal is to reach the d5 square with our knight.} 7. Bd3 (7. c4 $2
Bb4+ 8. Bd2 Ne3 9. Qa4+ Bd7 $19) 7... Be7 8. O-O (8. c4 Ne3 $11) 8... O-O 9. c4
(9. Qe2 Nc6 $3 10. c4 Ndb4 $3 $17 11. d5 Nxd3 12. Qxd3 Nb4 13. Qe2 Bf5 $19 14.
Bxf4 Re8 $19 {0-1 (31) Gareev,T-Sidhant, M/Chennai IND 2018/[,ÃéÜííçò]})
9... Ne3 10. Bxe3 fxe3 11. Qe2 Bg4 $1 $15 {Our idea IS NOT to play f5-f4.} 12.
Qxe3 Bxf3 $3 {We take it with the idea to disrupt his coordination! White
would always like to recapture f3 with his knight so now it is a good moment
to force him to take on f3 with another piece.} 13. Rxf3 Nc6 14. d5 Ne5 15.
Rff1 Ng4 $1 16. Qh3 f5 17. Be2 Nh6 18. Nf2 b6 19. Nd3 Bd6 $17) (5. Qe2 Ng6 6.
h4 h5 7. Nc3 c6 8. Bd2 Be7 9. O-O-O Bg4 10. exd5 O-O 11. dxc6 Nxc6 12. Qe4 Rc8
13. d5 Nb4 14. a3 Na6 15. Bxa6 bxa6 16. Qa4 Nxh4 17. d6 Bf6 18. Ne4 Nxf3 19.
Ba5 Rb8 20. gxf3 Bxb2+ 21. Kd2 Qd7 22. Qxd7 Bxd7 23. Rxh5 {1/2-1/2 Rapport,
R-Bacrot,E/Germany 2014/EXT 2015/[,ÃéÜííçò]}) (5. e5 $6 {A very bad
move for White and a typical mistake. Don't forget to play c5 soon!} Ng6 $15 6.
Bd3 (6. h4 h5 7. Bd3 c5 $1 (7... Be7 8. Bxg6 fxg6 9. Bxf4 O-O 10. Bg3 Bg4 11.
Nbd2 c5 $17 {White has a past pawn indeed but this is only a small not so
important factor. What matters is that we as Black have a very fast
development and White's king seems to be in trouble.}) 8. Bxg6 fxg6 9. Bxf4 Be7
$17 10. O-O O-O 11. Bg3 Nc6 $17) 6... c5 7. c3 Nc6 8. Bxg6 hxg6 9. Bxf4 Bg4 $19
10. Be3 Qb6 11. Qd2 Bxf3 $1 12. gxf3 O-O-O $17 13. O-O f6 14. f4 g5 $17) 5...
Nxd5 {Our idea is to play Be7, castle, Bg4, and Nc6, and every time we see the
move c4 we jump on e3, and we aren't afraid to give the pawn back because it
will cost White some time to regain the pawn.} 6. Bc4 Be6 $1 (6... Be7 7. O-O
c6 $1 $11) 7. Bb3 Nc6 $3 8. O-O Qf6 9. c4 Ne3 10. Bxe3 fxe3 11. d5 Qxb2 $15) (
4. Bb5 $6 c6 5. Ba4 d5 $17 6. Qe2 {White doesn't want to bring our knight to
d5.} d4 (6... Ng6 {Another interesting way for Black to play. I really like
this move. We sacrifice a pawn as well and we get a very good game with strong
pieces and fast development.} 7. exd5+ Be7 8. dxc6 Nxc6 9. O-O O-O 10. Bxc6
bxc6 $17) 7. Bb3 Ng6 8. Qc4 Qe7 9. Qxd4 c5 10. Qd3 Nc6 11. O-O Be6 $15 {
0-1 (30) Svidler,P-Bacrot,E/Porto-Vecchio FRA 2016/[,ÃéÜííçò]}) (4. Nc3
d5 5. exd5 (5. d4 dxe4 6. Nxe4 Nd5 {Transposes.}) 5... Nxd5 {[%cal Yf8e7,Ye8g8]
} 6. Nxd5 Qxd5 $15 7. d4 Be7 $1 8. Bd3 (8. c4 Qd6 9. Be2 g5 10. O-O Bf6 $17)
8... g5 $1 {This is one of the few times when we push g5!} 9. O-O Bg4 $15 10.
c3 Nc6 11. Qc2 O-O-O $17) 4... d5 $1 $15 5. exd5 (5. Bb3 $2 dxe4 6. Ng5 (6. Ne5
Be6 $19) 6... Nd5 $17 7. Qh5 g6 8. Nxf7 gxh5 9. Nxd8 c6 $19) 5... Nxd5 6. O-O
Be7 $5 (6... Be6 $1 $15 7. Qe2 Be7 8. Nc3 Nc6 $15) 7. d4 (7. Bb3 O-O 8. d4 Bg4
$36 (8... c6 $1 9. c4 Ne3 10. Bxe3 fxe3 11. Qe2 Bg4 $17 12. Qxe3 Bxf3 13. Rxf3
Bf6 $19) (8... c5 $1 9. c4 Ne3 10. Bxe3 fxe3 11. d5 Bf6 $17)) 7... c6 $3 {
We are not worried about giving the f4 pawn back. The move c6 is a key idea.
We want to get a strong pawn on d5 that can not be seriously attacked because
White does not have a light-squared bishop anymore, and with the d5 pawn, we
are stopping White's majority on the queenside for a long long time.} 8. Bxd5 (
8. Ne5 $6 Be6 9. Bxd5 cxd5 10. Bxf4 O-O 11. Nd2 f6 {An important move that
helps us to control the dark squares.} 12. Nd3 Nc6 $15 13. c3 b6 $15 14. Qf3
Qd7 15. Rae1 Rfe8 16. Kh1 Bf8 $17) 8... cxd5 9. Bxf4 Nc6 {We don't castle
first because we don't want to let White take our knight on b8 considering the
fact that White's bishop is a bad piece.} 10. c3 (10. Nc3 O-O 11. Kh1 Be6 $17)
10... O-O 11. Nbd2 {Black is already better because he has two very strong
bishops and good control.} Be6 $5 $15 {Still with the idea to play f6 next.} (
11... f6 $5 $15 {A great move that helps us take control of the dark squares.
White's idea often is to play Qe1-g3 followed by some Ne5, and Bh6 trying to
attack the Black's king and use the dark squares. By playing f6 this plan
won't be effective.} 12. Qe2 Re8 13. Qf2 Bf8 14. Rae1 Be6 15. Nb3 b6 $17) 12.
Qe1 (12. Kh1 f6 $1 13. Qe1 Qd7 14. Qg3 Rfe8 15. Rae1 Bf8 16. h3 Bf7 17. a3 Rxe1
18. Rxe1 Re8 19. Rxe8 Bxe8 {Capturing with the queen would lead to Bd6! and
White will very happily exchange one of our bishops.} 20. Nb3 b6 $17) 12... Re8
(12... Qd7 13. Qg3 f6 14. Bh6 Bd6 15. Bf4 Be7 16. Bh6 Rf7 17. Ne5 Nxe5 18. dxe5
Kh8 19. exf6 Bxf6 20. Be3 $17) 13. Qg3 Rc8 14. Ne5 Nxe5 15. Bxe5 f6 $17 *

