{[%evp 0,8,25,11,11,12,14,14,-15,5,32] Vienna game and Bishop Opening are the
only serious alternative to 2.Nf3. Those moves deserve serious attention. I
prepared for you easy-to-learn systems that transpose one to another. Aiming
with the knowledge from this lecture, you will be comfortable playing against
those openings.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nc6 {I decided to go for the more positional
and flexible 2...Nc6. I like this move because 3.f4 is not as dangerous (as in
2...Nf6). Also, Black keeps the option to develop the knight on "e7" in many
lines.} 3. Bc4 {This is the main line, and we can reach this position from
both Vienna Game and Bishop Opening} (3. f4 exf4 {is just good for Black}) (3.
Nf3 Nf6 {transposes to Four Knights Defence}) ({White has four different
options:} 3. g3 Bc5 $1 4. Bg2 d6 $1 {With the idea Ne7 followed by h5, gives
Black an excellent position}) 3... Nf6 4. d3 Bb4 {This is our first tabya. I
like it for Black because it cuts a lot of theory and is easy to play. White
has two systems: 5.Ne2 and 5.Nf3. Against the first one, we break the centre
with d7-d5 and get a good game. Against the second one, we exchange the bishop
on c3-square and then try to finish the development slowly} *

