{[%evp 0,68,21,10,5,5,21,5,3,-4,17,20,2,-2,36,6,2,3,4,10,74,66,54,54,27,29,29,
40,15,15,21,14,-3,12,25,25,19,-28,-33,-36,-38,-43,-43,-40,-49,-55,-49,-47,-47,
-44,-15,-20,-15,-20,-19,-17,-19,-12,-14,-14,-11,-11,-12,-12,-12,-11,-12,-13,
-13,-11,-10]} 1. e4 e5 {Today we are going to study the Vienna game and Bishop
Opening. There are mixed opinions about its objective evaluation. Some say it
is a very interesting variation while others believe black equalises.} 2. Nc3 {
Vienna game} (2. Bc4 {The Bishop's opening. It has some theory of itself, but
we can and we will transpose to the regular Vienna game!} Nf6 3. Nc3 (3. d3 Nc6
4. Nc3 (4. Nf3 Bc5) 4... Bb4) 3... Nc6 $1 (3... Nxe4 $5 {is also possible.} 4.
Qh5 Nd6) 4. d3 Bb4 {We find ourselves in the mainline of the Vienna game.})
2... Nc6 {Now white has three major options, 3.Bc4!? , 3.g3 and 3 .f4?!} 3. Bc4
{The mainline.} (3. g3 $5 Bc5 $1 {Our setup will be, Bc5-d6 and then either
develop with Nge7, or with f5-Nf6. But not with Nf6 blocking the f-pawn!} (3...
Nf6 $6 {Already a big inaccuracy because it blocks our f-pawn, thus stopping
future f5 breaks.} 4. Bg2 {Black can choose where to develop his f8-bishop.}
Be7 (4... Bc5 5. Nge2 d6 (5... h5 {Intresting possibility.} 6. h3 {White won't
meet with h4, rather this move stops black's plans.}) 6. d3 O-O 7. O-O a5 8. h3
{White is planning Kh2-f4} Nd4 9. Kh2 a4 {Black is planning a3 next. White can
choose to ignore it and continue with his plan or spend a tempo with} 10. a3 {
Next move is f4. These positions are tough to handle as black because he
doesn't have a clear plan. The problem again is we cannot play f5 or d5. The
f6-knight is misplaced.}) 5. Nge2 O-O 6. O-O d6 7. d3 $14 {We find ourselves
without any plan and white can next play f4 or Nd5. If Black wants to play
f7-f5, he needs to move the knight again. Unfortunately, there is no good
square for our knight. So, white is already better.}) (3... g6 $5 {playing
symmetrically is a very lazy ..but playable option!} 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. Nge2 d6 6.
O-O Nge7 7. d3 O-O 8. f4 f5 $132) 4. Bg2 d6 $1 {and now ... here are some
sample lines ...we don't need to memorize anything! ...just to know how to
develop the pieces! The plan is Nge7 and at a good moment f5.} 5. d3 (5. Na4 {
Another typical idea to gain the bishop pair.} Nge7 $1 {Very nice move leaving
the c5-bishop.} (5... Bd4 6. c3) 6. Nxc5 (6. Ne2 a5 $1 {We follow the same
idea forcing white to capture on c5. After taking twice on c5, the structure
is very comfortable for black.} (6... f6 $5 $36 {Computer suggests that this
move is good as well.}) 7. Nxc5 (7. d3 Ba7) 7... dxc5 8. f4 f6 $15 {Black is
already slightly better.} (8... Bg4 $5 $36) 9. d3 Be6 10. O-O Qd6 $36 (10...
Qd7 $36 11. Be3 b6 12. f5 (12. fxe5 Nxe5 (12... fxe5) 13. Nf4 Bf7 14. Bh3 Qd6)
12... Bf7 13. Qe1 Nb4 14. Qc1 Nxa2 15. Qd2 Nb4 16. Nc3 O-O-O 17. Qf2 Nec6 18.
Nb5 Nd4 19. Nxd4 cxd4 20. Bd2 Nxc2 21. Rac1 Ne3 22. Bxe3 dxe3 23. Qxe3 Qd4 {
0-1 Popovic,D-Grischuk,A/Chess. com INT 2019/EXT 2021}) 11. Be3 b6 12. Qd2
O-O-O {We don't mind castling long even after moves like a5-b6 because we have
good center control.}) (6. d3 a5 $1 $132 {Threatning Ba7.} 7. Nxc5 dxc5 {
We have a good center control. Next up is Qd6-Be6}) 6... dxc5 7. d3 h5 $1 (7...
Be6 8. f4 f6 $132 9. Nf3 Qd6) 8. Be3 Qd6 $132 9. h3 h4 10. g4 f6 $3 11. Ne2 g5
$3 $17) (5. Nge2 Nge7 6. O-O h5 7. h3 {White cannot allow us to push h4.} Be6
8. d3 (8. Nd5 Qd7 9. Kh2 {If the e7 knight was placed on f6, we would have
problems carrying out our plan. Fortunately, here we can simply play} f5 $132 {
We have a very good play.} 10. d3 $2 h4 {Black is already better.}) 8... Qd7 9.
Kh2 d5 $132) 5... Nge7 $1 {from e7 , the knight can go to g6..after the moves
1...h5 2.h3-h4 3. g4-Ng6!} (5... f5 $5 {a bit more risky but also playable} 6.
Qh5+ $1 (6. Nge2 Nf6 {is playble only after we have played f5.} 7. Na4 fxe4 8.
dxe4 O-O 9. Nxc5 dxc5 $132) 6... g6 7. Qd1 {White loses two tempi (Qh5-Qd1)
but it weakened dark squares around the king by g6.} Nf6 (7... a5 $132) 8. Na4
h6 9. Nxc5 dxc5 $132) 6. Na4 (6. f4 $2 {This move is premature and wrong.} exf4
7. Bxf4 (7. gxf4 Ng6 $19 {The usual follow-up would be f5 but here the queen/
knight can go to h4.} 8. Nf3 Bg4 9. h3 Bxf3 10. Qxf3 Nd4 {Black is better.
White has a weak king very early on in the opening.}) 7... Ng6 8. Bd2 Nh4 $3
$17 9. Bh3 Qf6 10. Bf4 Bxg1) (6. Nge2 h5 (6... a5)) 6... h5 $1 (6... a5 $132)
7. h3 f6 $1 {Not at all necessary but a very good move according to the engine.
} 8. Ne2 a5 9. Nxc5 dxc5 $132 10. O-O Be6 11. f4 Qd7 12. Kh2 O-O-O $36 13. fxe5
Nxe5 14. Nf4 N7c6 15. Be3 b6 $17) (3. Nf3 Nf6 {this transposes to the 4 knight
defenses of course!}) (3. f4 $6 exf4 4. Nf3 (4. d4 $2 Qh4+ 5. Ke2 d6 (5... b6
$36) 6. Nf3 Bg4 $36 7. Bxf4 O-O-O 8. Be3 Qh5) 4... g5 $3 $15 {after 4...g5
black is better ...but white has practical chances so I need to be careful! ...
it is still a game!} 5. Bc4 (5. d4 $2 g4 6. Ng1 Qh4+ 7. Ke2 Bh6 $17 8. Nd5 Kd8
$17 (8... Nf6 $3 $19)) (5. h4 $6 g4 6. Ng5 d6 7. d4 (7. Bc4 Ne5) 7... h6 8.
Nxf7 Kxf7 9. Bc4+ Kg7 10. Bxf4 Rh7 $3 11. Qd3 Kh8 $17 12. O-O-O Bg7) 5... g4
$17 (5... Bg7 $1 6. d4 d6 7. h4 h6 $1 $17 8. Qd3 Bg4 $1) 6. O-O gxf3 7. d4 (7.
Qxf3 Qh4) (7. Bxf7+ Kxf7 8. Qxf3 Qh4 $19 {see the game session} (8... Bh6 $5))
7... Bg7 $19 8. e5 d6 9. Bxf4 dxe5 10. Be3 Bg4 11. Qe1 Nge7 12. h3 Bh5 13. Bg5
f6 14. Be3 Qd7 15. Rd1 O-O-O 16. dxe5 f2+ 17. Bxf2 Bxd1 18. exf6 Bxf6 19. Be6
Bxc2 20. Bxd7+ Rxd7 21. Bg3 Bd4+ 22. Kh2 a6 23. Ne4 Nd5 24. Ng5 Bg6 25. Ne6 Re8
26. Qe2 Ne3 27. Nxd4 Nxd4 28. Qf2 Nxf1+ 29. Qxf1 Be4 30. b4 Bc6 31. a4 Re2 32.
Qf8+ Rd8 33. Qg7 Rxg2+ 34. Kh1 Rxg3+ {0-1 Beerdsen,T-Paravyan,D/Lichess.org
INT 2021/CBM 202 Extra}) 3... Nf6 4. d3 (4. Nf3 Nxe4 $1 {is the Italian 4
knights}) (4. Nge2 $2 {This move is simply bad because of} Nxe4 5. Nxe4 d5 6.
Bd3 dxe4 7. Bxe4 Bd7 $3 (7... Bd6 8. O-O O-O $15) 8. O-O f5 9. Bd5 Qf6 $17)
4... Bb4 {By this move order, we transpose to the Vienna game and we can avoid
the bishop opening, where we have good play! 1.e4-e5 2.Nc3-Nc6 3.Bc4-Nf6 4.
d3-Bb4 !'} 5. Nge2 {[%emt 0:00:13] White wants to play f4 in the long run, so
he is not blocking his f-pawn.} (5. Nf3 $5 {Extremely rare but playable.} d6 6.
O-O (6. Bd2 O-O 7. Nd5 Bxd2+ 8. Qxd2 Nxd5 9. Bxd5 Ne7 10. Bb3 a5 $1 11. a4 Ng6
12. O-O Kh8 13. d4 Qe7 14. dxe5 dxe5 15. Qe3 Bg4 16. Rfd1 Bxf3 17. Qxf3 Kg8 18.
Rd2 Rfd8) 6... Bxc3 7. bxc3 h6 $132 (7... Be6 $5 8. Bb3 h6 9. Re1 O-O 10. h3
$14) 8. Re1 O-O 9. h3 Na5 10. Bb3 c5 $132 11. c4 Nh7 12. Bd2 f5) (5. Bd2 d6 (
5... Bxc3 6. Bxc3 d5)) 5... d5 {[%emt 0:00:05]} 6. exd5 {[%emt 0:00:34]} Nxd5 {
[%emt 0:00:04]} 7. O-O $1 {[%emt 0:00:36]} (7. Bxd5 $2 Qxd5 8. O-O Qd8 $15 {
This move is possible as well.} (8... Qd7 $3 $15 {Planning b6-Bb7. White
doesn't have a light-squared bishop, so black's queen is well placed on d7.} 9.
a3 Be7)) (7. Bd2 Be6 8. O-O (8. Bxd5 Bxd5 9. Nxd5 Qxd5 $15) 8... O-O $132) (7.
a3 Nxc3 8. Nxc3 (8. bxc3 Bc5) 8... Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Qd6 10. O-O Be6 11. Bxe6 Qxe6
12. f4 (12. Bd2 O-O 13. f4 exf4 14. Bxf4 Qd7 15. Qf3 Nd8 16. Rae1 c6 17. d4 Ne6
18. Kh1 Nxf4 19. Qxf4 Rfe8) 12... O-O-O $132 {with a great position for black!
... it is, in fact, white who has to be very careful here, because of his bad
pawn structure!}) 7... Be6 $1 {[%emt 0:00:04] Anish Giri has played many games
as black in this line. Make sure to know this line very well, because it is
very popular.} 8. Bxd5 $1 {[%emt 0:08:06]} (8. Nxd5 $6 Bxd5 9. Bxd5 Qxd5 10. c3
Be7 $15 {Black is very slightly better because of better center control. White
can play f4 but that creates some weakness as well.}) (8. Bd2 O-O 9. a3 Be7 10.
Bxd5 Bxd5 11. f4 f5 12. fxe5 Nxe5 13. Nxd5 Qxd5 14. Kh1 Rae8 15. Nf4 Qd7 16.
Bc3 Bd6 17. h3 c6 18. Qd2 Re7 19. b3 Rfe8 20. Rf2 g6 21. a4 Nf7 22. Raf1 Be5
23. Bb4 Bd6 24. Bc3 Be5 25. Bb4 Bd6 26. Bc3 Be5 27. Bb4 Bd6 28. Bc3 Be5 29. Bb4
Bd6 {1/2-1/2 Sanal, V-Matlakov,M/Almaty KAZ 2022/The Week in Chess 1469}) (8.
a3 $6 Bxc3 9. bxc3 Qd6 $132 {The position is objectively equal. However once
the position is simplified, white's broken pawn structure will create many
practical chances for black.}) (8. Bb3 O-O 9. a3 Be7 $15) (8. f4 $4 Nxc3 9.
bxc3 Bc5+ 10. Kh1 Bxc4 11. dxc4 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 Bd6 $19) 8... Bxd5 {[%emt 0:00:
08]} 9. f4 $1 {[%emt 0:00:02] Very common move in the vienna.} f6 $5 {[%emt 0:
00:06] The key move to save this position which was introduced by Anish Giri.}
(9... O-O $6 {This is a mistake because of} 10. f5 {White is intending f6 next.
} f6 {Planning Bf7 to keep the bishop pair.} 11. Nxd5 Qxd5 12. Ng3 $1 {White
will hop on e4 next with a great position.} Rad8 13. Ne4 Be7 14. Be3 Qd7 15.
Qf3 Nd4 16. Qf2 {e4 is a strong outpost for white but d4 isn't really a good
outpost for black as it can be kicked or exchanged. So white is very
comfortable.}) 10. fxe5 {[%emt 0:02:42]} (10. f5 $2 {White next wants to play
Nxd5 next and get his e2 knight on e4 as well. However it's black to play and
we can meet this plan with} Bf7 $1 $17 {Keeping the bishop pair, black is fine.
} 11. Be3 Qd7 12. Ne4 O-O-O $17 13. a3 Be7 14. b4 g6 $2 (14... Nd4 15. Bxd4
exd4 16. Qd2 Rhe8 17. a4 (17. Nf4 Qxf5) 17... Bf8 $17 18. b5 Re5 19. N2g3 Bd5)
15. N2g3 Nd4 16. fxg6 Bxg6 17. Nxf6 Qc6 18. Bxd4 Rxd4 19. Nfe4 h5 20. Qe2 Qe6
21. Qf3 Rf8 22. Qxf8+ Bxf8 23. Rxf8+ Rd8 24. Raf1 b6 25. Rxd8+ Kxd8 26. Rf8+
Ke7 27. Rf6 Qg4 28. Rc6 h4 29. Nf6 Qd4+ {0-1 Shevtchenko,O-Pap,G/ chess.com
INT 2023/[,ГйЬннзт]}) (10. Nxd5 Qxd5 11. fxe5 (11. f5 O-O-O {We are
next planning h5/g6 with a dynamic game.}) 11... Nxe5 12. d4 O-O-O 13. c3 Bd6
