{[%evp 0,46,18,11,11,11,23,-20,-16,-18,-8,-12,17,17,17,22,28,28,20,28,19,19,28,
23,23,20,13,10,14,-24,-31,-31,-48,-101,-80,-88,-93,-110,-102,-153,-161,-207,
-207,-201,-215,-207,-215,-211,-178] This is a blitz game between Popovic Dusan
and Grischuk Alexander. It is a blitz game because not many people play Vienna
in serious games.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 Bc5 4. Bg2 d6 5. Na4 (5. Nge2 Nge7
{Playing Nge7 is better over Nf6 to not block the f-pawn.}) 5... a5 {Grischuk
decided to force white to capture on c5. Generally, we want to keep the pawn
on a5 instead of a6 in this variation.} 6. Nxc5 dxc5 7. d3 Nge7 {Black should
not play ...Nf6 stopping his f-pawn.} 8. Ne2 Be6 9. O-O Qd7 {Black is planning
Bh3 to trade the light-squared bishop. Next, he can play h5-h4 for attack or
positionally after Bxg2-0-0} 10. f4 (10. b3 Bh3 11. Bb2 h5 (11... Bxg2 12. Kxg2
O-O 13. f4 f6 14. f5 {We are not afraid of this king's Indian setup. As we have
} a4 {Black has played on the queenside and good center control.})) 10... f6 {
The typical way to meet f4} 11. Be3 b6 12. f5 (12. fxe5 Nxe5 {Both recaptures
are sound.} (12... fxe5 {Black will next castle long. White's e2 knight is
poorly placed.}) 13. Nf4 Bf7 14. Bh3 Qd6 {Black will next castle short.}) 12...
Bf7 13. Qe1 Nb4 14. Qc1 Nxa2 {Black decided to take the a2-pawn.} 15. Qd2 Nb4
16. Nc3 O-O-O 17. Qf2 Nec6 18. Nb5 Nd4 {Stabalizing the position.} 19. Nxd4
cxd4 20. Bd2 Nxc2 21. Rac1 Ne3 22. Bxe3 dxe3 23. Qxe3 Qd4 {Black is better and
he won later.} 0-1

