{[%evp 0,14,21,13,13,13,12,12,12,5,5,13,13,7,18,18,18]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3.
Nc3 Nf6 {In this lecture, I analyze all White's options besides 4.d4 White
tried plenty of moves on move four like 4.h3, 4.a3, 4.Be2 The simple rule is
that Black is doing OK after 4...d5} 4. Bb5 {I prefer the move:} Bb4 {This is
the old main line which is more positional and does not include long forced
lines. There are two main directions:} 5. O-O O-O 6. d3 (6. Bxc6 $5 {Reaching
a well-known structure which can be reached from the Exchange Ruy Lopez. Both
sides have pros and cons, but I like that we have good chances to outplay the
opponent in this non-symmetrical position.} dxc6 7. d3) 6... Bxc3 $1 {It is
important not to allow Ne2-g3 maneuver.} 7. bxc3 d6 {For the moment, Black has
the better pawn structure to compensate for his opponent's pair of bishops.
White has three approaches: 1) Complete development and pin Black's king's
knight. 2) Take on c6 to keep the game symmetrical. 3) Make a useful waiting
move. In all cases, Black has adequate counterplay} *

