[BlackTeamCountry "GER"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 {White has tried many "little"
semi-waiting moves here, aiming for some kind of Four Knights scenario with
reversed colours under slightly favourable circumstances. While this approach
is generally harmless and can be met in many different ways. To reach a
complicated and combative position it's usually a good idea to play 4...d5 and
transpose into a reversed Scotch.} (4. a3 d5 (4... g6 $5 {Igor Glek's
variation with reversed colours! When development on the diagonal f8-a3 is
restricted, what's more natural than a fianchetto?} 5. d4 {Generally, this is
the critical move against setups with an early g7-g6. However, the tempo
wasted on a2-a3 renders it rather harmless:} (5. Bc4 Bg7 6. d3 d6 7. O-O h6
$132 {, followed by 0-0, and Black has no problems.}) (5. Bb5 Bg7 6. O-O O-O 7.
Bxc6 $6 dxc6 8. Nxe5 $2 Re8 $17) 5... exd4 6. Nxd4 Bg7 $132) 5. Bb5 (5. exd5
Nxd5 6. Bb5 Nxc3 7. bxc3 Bd6 8. O-O O-O $132) 5... Nxe4 6. Nxe5 Qf6 7. Nf3 Be6
8. O-O Bd6 $132 (8... O-O-O $5 9. Bxc6 bxc6 10. Qe2 Kb7 $13)) (4. h3 d5 (4...
Bb4 $11 {is also easily good enough, playing the topic of this lecture with
reversed colours.}) 5. exd5 (5. Bb5 Nxe4 6. Nxe5 Qf6 7. Nf3 Be6 $132) 5... Nxd5
6. Bb5 Nxc3 7. bxc3 Bd6 8. d4 exd4 9. cxd4 O-O $132) (4. Be2 d5 (4... Bb4 $5 5.
Nd5 Be7 $132) 5. exd5 Nxd5 6. d3 (6. O-O Nxc3 7. bxc3 e4 8. Ne1 Bd6 $15) 6...
Nxc3 7. bxc3 Bd6 $132) (4. a4 $6 {was once tried by Carlsen in a blitz game
but can hardly be considered a serious move, as the weakening of the b4-square
is quite relevant.} a6 $5 (4... d5 5. Bb5 Nxe4 6. Nxe5 Qf6 7. Nf3 Be6 $132) 5.
d4 (5. Bc4 Nxe4 $11) 5... exd4 6. Nxd4 Bb4 $132) (4. Bc4 Nxe4 5. Bxf7+ (5. Nxe4
d5 6. Bd3 (6. Bb5 dxe4 7. Nxe5 Qd5 $17) 6... dxe4 7. Bxe4 Bd6 8. O-O O-O 9. Re1
Nb4 $1 $132 {Followed by f7-f5, with good play.}) 5... Kxf7 6. Nxe4 d5 $17) (4.
d4 exd4 5. Nxd4 Bb4 {is already covered in the lecture on the Scotch.}) (4. g3
$5 {Igor Glek's system has been fashionable about 20 years ago, but several
good remedies for Black have been found, for example:} d5 (4... Bc5 $5 5. Bg2 (
5. Nxe5 $4 Nxe5 6. d4 Bxd4 $1 $19) 5... d6 6. d3 a5 $132) 5. exd5 Nxd5 6. Bg2
Nxc3 7. bxc3 Bd6 (7... Bc5 $5 8. O-O O-O 9. d3 Bg4 $132) 8. O-O O-O 9. d4 h6 $5
$132) 4... Bb4 {Black has several good alternatives:} (4... Bd6) (4... Bc5) (
4... Nd4 5. Nxd4 exd4 6. e5 dxc3 7. exf6 $11) 5. O-O (5. Nd5 $6 Nxd5 $1 6. exd5
e4 $1 7. dxc6 (7. Qe2 $2 O-O $17 8. dxc6 dxc6) 7... dxc6 8. Be2 exf3 9. Bxf3
Be6 10. O-O Qd7 $15 {, followed by 0-0-0.}) 5... O-O {Now White is at a
crossroads:} 6. d3 (6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. d3 (7. Nxe5 {The most drawish line in the
Four Knights, but even here Black has ways to create problems for his
unambitious opponent.} Re8 8. Nd3 (8. Nf3 $2 Nxe4 9. Nxe4 Rxe4 10. d3 Re8 11.
Bd2 Bd6 12. Bg5 Qd7 $15) 8... Bxc3 9. dxc3 Nxe4 10. Qf3 (10. Bf4 Nd6 $11) 10...
Nd6 11. Bf4 (11. Be3 Qh4 $132 (11... a5 $132)) 11... Qh4 $132 (11... Qf6 $132))
(7. Re1 Re8 8. d3 Nd7 $132) 7... Nd7 $1 {Black's knight may look unimpressive
now, but within just a few moves it may very well become the strongest minor
piece on the board.} (7... Re8 $5) 8. Bd2 (8. Ne2 Re8 9. Ng3 (9. Bd2 Bf8 10.
Ng3 c5 $132) 9... Bf8 10. b3 Nc5 $1 (10... a5 11. a4 c5 12. Bb2 f6 $132) 11.
Bb2 f6 12. Nh4 Ne6 $36) (8. a3 Bd6 9. Nd2 Nb6 $132) 8... Re8 9. Ne2 Bf8 10. Ng3
Nc5 $5 (10... c5 11. Re1 a5 12. a4 Nb8 $1 $132 (12... f6 $132)) 11. h3 (11. b4
Na4 $36) 11... f6 12. a4 a5 13. b3 Ne6 $132) {After fortifying e4, White
intends to continue with the manoeuvre Nc3-e2-g3, followed by an eventual
c2-c3 and d3-d4. This can be prevented by playing} 6... Bxc3 $1 ({Also fully
playable is} 6... d6 7. Ne2 Ne7 8. c3 Ba5 9. Ng3 c6 10. Ba4 Ng6) 7. bxc3 d6 {
For the moment, Black has the better pawn structure to compensate for his
opponent's pair of bishops. Now White has three different approaches: 1)
Complete development and pin Black's king's knight. 2) Take on c6 to keep the
game symmetrical. 3) Make a useful waiting move.} 8. Bg5 {The main move.} (8.
Bxc6 bxc6 9. Bg5 {This logical continuation surprisingly offers Black good
chances to become active soon:} (9. Qe2 c5 $11) (9. Rb1 h6 (9... Nd7 $11) 10.
h3 Be6 11. c4 Nd7 12. Be3 c5 13. Nd2 f5 $132) 9... h6 10. Bh4 Qe7 $1 {After
White has commited the bishop to the kingside, Black should unpin his knight
as quickly as possible.} 11. Re1 (11. c4 Qe6 12. Re1 c5 {Now after another
neutral move by White, Black already has the better chances:} 13. Qd2 Nd7 (
13... Nh5 $15) (13... Nh7 $15) 14. a4 (14. h3 f5 $15) 14... Bb7 15. Rab1 Bc6
16. a5 f5 $15) 11... Qe6 $1 {Again, unpinning the knight and preparing to
exploit the soon-misplaced bishop's position on h4.} 12. d4 $6 (12. Bxf6 Qxf6
13. Nd2 Qg6 (13... Be6 14. c4 c5 $132) 14. Nf1 f5 $36) 12... Nd7 $36 13. dxe5
dxe5 14. Nd2 Nb6 $15 {With a position similar to the game Hou Yifan - Karpov.})
(8. Re1 h6 $1 {Preventing Bg5 is generally a good answer against White's
waiting approaches.} (8... Nb8 $5 {is another interesting approach.} 9. d4 Nbd7
10. Rb1 c6 11. Bd3 Re8 12. Ba3 Qc7 $132 {Followed by an eventual c6-c5.}) 9. d4
Bd7 $1 10. Rb1 (10. Bxc6 $2 {This is of course a bad idea, giving up the
bishop pair without any structural or dynamic benefit.} Bxc6 11. dxe5 dxe5 $1
12. Nxe5 Qxd1 $17 (12... Bxe4 $17) 13. Rxd1 Bxe4 14. Nd3 Rfe8 $17) 10... b6 11.
h3 Re8 $132 (11... Qe8 $132) 12. Bd3 Nh7 $1 (12... Na5 $5 13. Bd2 c5 14. d5 c4
15. Bf1 Rc8 $132) 13. Be3 Qf6 $132) (8. Rb1 h6 {will likely transpose to one
of the other lines.} (8... Ne7 $5)) 8... h6 $1 (8... Nb8 $5 {may be the most
ambitious way to handle this type of position. The computer doesn't like this
approach very much but in practice it's very difficult to find anything that
comes close to a refutation.} 9. Re1 (9. d4 Qe7 10. Re1 h6 11. Bh4 c6 12. Bf1
Nbd7 $132 {Now for example} 13. c4 {should be answered with} c5 {, leading to
a Nimzo-Indian type position after} 14. c3 Re8 {, followed by Nf8-g6.}) 9... h6
10. Bh4 c6 11. Bc4 Nbd7 12. d4 Re8 $132 {For example} 13. h3 Qe7 14. Qd3 Nf8
15. Rad1 Ng6 {, and Black can start active play on the kingside with Nh5 soon.}
) (8... Bd7 $5) (8... Qe7 $5) 9. Bh4 Bd7 10. Re1 (10. d4 Re8 11. Re1 a6 (11...
Ne7 $6 12. Rb1 $1 $14) 12. Ba4 Ne7 $1 13. Bxd7 Nxd7 $132 14. Qd3 Qc8 15. h3 Ng6
16. Bg3 Nf6 17. Rab1 Nh5 $36) (10. Rb1 a6 11. Ba4 b6 $1 12. Bb3 (12. Re1 Ne7 $1
$132) 12... Qe7 13. Re1 Rae8 (13... Kh8 $132) 14. d4 Bg4 $132) 10... a6 {
An important preparatory move for the following tactic:} (10... Ne7 $6 11. Rb1
$14) 11. Ba4 (11. Bc4 $5 Na5 12. Bb3 Qe7 13. d4 Rad8 $132) 11... Ne7 $1 12.
Bxd7 (12. Bb3 g5 $5 (12... Ng6 13. Bg3 Kh8 $132 (13... b5 14. a4 c5 $132)) 13.
Bg3 Ng6 14. d4 Qe7 $132) (12. Bxf6 Bxa4 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. Rb1 Rab8 15. c4 Bd7
$15 {Black is ready to play b7-b5 next, after which White's a-pawn will become
very weak.}) 12... Nxd7 13. d4 Qe8 $132 {Black will play Ng6 and Nf6, followed
by Nh5, with a good position.} *

