1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 Bb4 5. O-O O-O 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. Nxe5 Re8
8. Nd3 Bxc3 9. dxc3 Nxe4 10. Qf3 Nd6 11. Be3 Qh4 12. Qf4 (12. Qg3 Qxg3 13. hxg3
{does not promise White an easy draw, for example} Bf5 14. Rfe1 f6 15. Rad1 (
15. f3 h5 16. Kf2 g5 17. Rh1 Bg6 18. Rad1 b6 19. Rhe1 c5 20. Bd2 Kf7 21. Rxe8
Rxe8 22. Re1 Rc8 23. b3 c4 $17) 15... h5 16. f3 g5 $15) 12... Qh5 13. Rfe1 Qf5
14. Qxf5 Bxf5 15. Rad1 f6 16. f3 Re7 17. Kf2 Kf7 18. Bc5 Rxe1 19. Rxe1 b6 20.
Be3 ({Better was} 20. Bxd6 cxd6 21. g4 $11 {, with an equal position but not a
trivial draw yet.}) 20... c5 21. Re2 a5 $1 $15 22. a4 g5 23. Ne1 Bd7 $1 24. b3
c4 $1 $17 {Now White's pawns on the light squares become very vulnerable,
while the e3-bishop has no access to any of his opponent's pawns, even though
they are almost all on dark squares.} 25. Rd2 Ke7 26. Rd1 Be6 $1 {Putting
pressure on b3 and trying to provoke bxc4.} 27. Rb1 h5 $1 28. g3 Bf5 29. Rd1
Be6 30. Rb1 Bd5 31. Ke2 Kd7 32. Bd4 f5 33. Bf6 g4 34. Bd4 Re8+ $1 35. Kf2 c5
36. Bg7 Bxf3 $2 {The correct idea, but Black had to resolve the tension on the
queenside first:} (36... cxb3 $1 37. cxb3 Bxf3 $1 38. Nxf3 Ne4+ 39. Ke3 Nxc3+
40. Ne5+ Rxe5+ 41. Bxe5 Nxb1 42. Kd3 b5 43. axb5 Na3 44. Bc3 Nxb5 45. Bxa5 Nd4
$19) 37. Nxf3 Ne4+ 38. Kg2 $2 (38. Ke3 $1 gxf3 ({Or} 38... Nxc3+ 39. Ne5+ Rxe5+
40. Bxe5 Nxb1 41. bxc4 Ke6 42. Bb2 $15) 39. Rd1+ Ke7 40. Kxf3 Ng5+ 41. Kg2 Kf7
42. Bh6 Ne4 $15) 38... gxf3+ 39. Kh1 cxb3 40. cxb3 Nd2 41. Rd1 Kc6 42. Bh6 Nxb3
43. Rf1 b5 44. axb5+ Kxb5 45. Rxf3 a4 46. Rxf5 a3 47. Rf2 Ra8 48. Ra2 Kc4 49.
Bg7 Nc1 50. Ra1 a2 51. Rxc1 Rb8 0-1

