1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. O-O O-O 6. d3 d6 7. Bg5 Bxc3 8.
bxc3 Qe7 9. Re1 a6 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. d4 a5 12. Rb1 Qe6 13. a3 Nd7 14. Nh4 f6
15. Bc1 Nb6 16. Nf5 Nc4 17. Ne3 Ba6 18. f4 Nxe3 19. Bxe3 Qc4 20. Qd2 Rae8 21.
fxe5 fxe5 22. Bf2 h6 $1 23. h3 Rf7 24. Bg3 Kh7 25. Kh2 Bb5 $1 26. Rbd1 Re6 27.
Ra1 Ba4 28. dxe5 dxe5 29. Rac1 Qc5 30. Qe3 Qxe3 31. Rxe3 Rd7 {An endgame with
mutual weaknesses has arisen, most notably Black's e5-pawn vs. White's c2-pawn.
} 32. Rd3 Rdd6 {If either side can force the other to capture and repair the
broken pawn structure, he or she will be clearly better. As it turns out,
Black is better positioned to win this battle:} 33. Kg1 Bb5 $1 34. Rdd1 Be2 $1
{Now White has to leave the d-file in order to avoid an unfavourable rook
trade.} 35. Re1 Rd2 36. Bf2 Bb5 {Threatening to win the c2-pawn with Ba4.} 37.
Be3 {Ejecting the rook from the second rank in time, but now White's bishop is
far away from putting pressure on e5 and Black's passive rook can join the
action.} Rd7 38. Rcd1 Red6 $17 {Now White decided that trading rooks and
neutralising the pressure is the lesser evil compared to being tied down with
a rook on c1. However, Black's improved pawn structure will turn out to be
decisive:} 39. Rxd6 cxd6 40. Bb6 $1 {Forcing Black to block the a4-square with
a pawn.} a4 41. Be3 c5 42. Kf2 Rf7+ 43. Kg3 Rf6 44. Bd2 (44. Rb1 Bc6 $17) 44...
Kg8 45. Re3 Bc6 ({Black would like to activate the king, but after} 45... Kf7
$2 46. Rf3 $15 {, the opposite-coloured bishop ending offers Black good
drawing chances.}) 46. Re2 Rf1 47. Be1 Kf7 48. c4 ({Now however,} 48. Rf2+ {
drops the e4-pawn and leads to a dead lost position.} Rxf2 49. Bxf2 Bxe4 $19)
48... Ke6 49. Bd2 Ra1 50. Re3 Ra2 $19 {White has too many weaknesses and no
counterplay.} 51. Kf3 Rxc2 52. Bc3 Bb7 53. g3 Ba6 54. Be1 Bxc4 55. Rc3 Be2+ 56.
Ke3 Ra2 57. Bd2 Bf1 58. h4 Bh3 59. Bc1 Bf1 60. Bd2 Kd7 61. Bc1 Kc6 62. Kf3 Be2+
63. Ke3 Bh5 64. Bd2 Bg4 65. Kd3 Kb5 66. Ke3 c4 $1 0-1

