{[%evp 0,20,21,13,13,13,15,9,9,9,9,9,19,13,13,13,13,13,31,7,7,-21,24]} 1. e4 e5
2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 (3. c3 {The Ponziani is not a very popular opening, but we
need to know what to do against it. There is more than one way to get a good
position. In this lecture, I show the "simplest" solution.} Nf6 4. d4 {is the
most ambitious, and the position resembles the "Alapin" Sicilian. Black can
continue:} (4. d3 d5 {We achieve a Philidor type of position with reversed
colors.}) 4... exd4 5. e5 Nd5 6. cxd4 Bb4+ {With a good game}) 3... exd4 4.
Nxd4 (4. c3 {The so-called Goring Gambit is not dangerous at all. Black has a
well know equalizer, which you should remember. The theory goes:} d5 5. exd5
Qxd5 6. cxd4 Bg4 7. Nc3 Bb4 8. Be2 Bxf3 $1 9. Bxf3 Qc4 {with a very good
position for Black}) 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 {We can get this position with the 3.Nc3
move order as well. The Four Knights Scotch is a very annoying and serious
option for White. Sometimes is really hard to play for a win with Black. I
believe that I suggest quite an interesting and fighting option for Black.} Bb4
6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. Bd3 d5 8. exd5 O-O 9. O-O cxd5 10. Bg5 Be6 {Rare, but strong
move. With the idea to play c7-c5 in one move. The arising positions are quite
sharp and playable. I believe that Black is doing very well.} *

