{[%evp 0,64,16,28,25,28,28,12,5,33,17,-7,18,11,5,12,1,4,2,2,2,0,24,1,-6,8,8,7,
7,-22,-8,-21,-13,-4,-4,-26,-26,-25,-12,-28,28,-16,-39,-12,-39,-30,10,-107,-97,
-124,-121,-138,-125,-173,-159,-189,-202,-264,-285,-285,-303,-282,-301,-297,
-290,-294,-294]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 {This line is very well known and
very important. Because We can also get the same position from two different
move orders.} (3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 (4... Bb4 $5) 5. Nxd4 (5. Nd5 {This is a
tricky idea but black stays better after} Nb4 $3 $15 {Very easy move to
remember because it is so unique.} 6. Nxd4 Nfxd5 (6... Nxe4) 7. exd5 Nxd5 8.
Nf5 $1 Ne7 $3 $17 {the ONLY move is 8...Ne7!! ? in order not to lose at once...
but win!!!} 9. Bg5 d5 $1 (9... f6 $17) 10. Bxe7 Bxe7 11. Nxg7+ Kf8 12. Nh5 Rg8
13. Ng3 Bf6 $15) 5... Bb4 {Transposes to the mainline.}) 3... exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{There are two main options for black. 4... Nf6 and 4... Bc6. I believe 4...
Nf6 is objectively better.} 5. Nc3 Bb4 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. Bd3 (7. Qd4 $6 Qe7 8. f3
Bc5 9. Qd3 d5 10. Be3 Bb6 $36) 7... O-O {We can also play ...d5 immediately.}
8. O-O d5 9. exd5 (9. Bd2 {This is another deviation when the most popular
move is to take twice on c3 and the endgames are very drawish. But we have a
very interesting alternative.} Rb8 $1 {This rare move will leave White players
out of the book.} (9... a5 {This move is also possible.}) 10. Re1 (10. e5 Ng4
11. f4 (11. Bf4 f6 12. exf6 Qxf6 $36) 11... Bc5+ 12. Kh1 Qh4 13. h3 Qg3 14.
hxg4 Qh4#) 10... Bg4 11. Qc1 Re8 $132) 9... cxd5 {Our problem with black here
is that the position tends to be very drawish and we want to find ways to play
for a win! Though, I found some very interesting ways to fight for a win.} 10.
Bg5 {The most common move and the mainline.} (10. h3 {Now Black has many ways
to play. For example 10... c6/10... Re8.} h6 $132 {Stopping Bg5. It is always
beneficial for black to exchange the dark-squared bishops.} (10... Re8 $132)
11. Qf3 Be6 12. Bf4 c5 $132 13. a3 Ba5 14. Rad1 Bc7 15. Bxc7 Qxc7 {Due to the
absence of a dark-squared bishop our knight on f6 is very stable. Which means
there are no attacking chances for white.}) (10. Bd2 $6 c5 $1 {We shouldn't
follow the rule of trading dark-squared bishop by playing ...d4 as that rule
only applies to the position where black's pawn is on d5. The d4 push changes
the dynamics of the position.} (10... Rb8 {This move is also possible.}) (10...
Re8 {This move is also possible.}) (10... Bg4 $1 11. f3 (11. Be2 Bf5 $36 (11...
Be6 $36 12. Nb5 Bxd2 13. Qxd2 c5 $36)) 11... Be6 $15) 11. a3 Ba5 {We are happy
to trade the dark-squared bishops.} 12. Na2 (12. Bg5 Be6 13. Qf3 h6 (13... Rb8
14. b4 cxb4 15. Nb5 Bd7 16. axb4 Bxb4 17. Nxa7 Rb6) 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. Nxd5 Qxf3
16. Ne7+ Kh8 17. gxf3 Bd8 $132) 12... Bxd2 (12... Bc7 $3 $17) 13. Qxd2 a5 {
We can play for a win!}) 10... Be6 $5 {The idea of 10...Be6 instead of the
much more common 10. ..c6 , is to place the -c pawn on c5 in one go, If
possible. Black next wants to play h6/c5/Rb8. Most likely h6.} (10... c6 {
The most common move.} 11. Qf3 h6 $5 (11... Be7 $5 {this is objectively
slightly better for white..but it allows black to keep on fighting for a win! .
..as GM Jussupow had once told me: quite often, the easiest way to play for a
win with black, is to pass from a slightly worse position! (rather than play
the best moves that lead to an easy draw in the opening! )}) 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13.
Qxf6 gxf6 14. Ne2 {This is the position that we want to avoid generally...
because it is very drawish...and there are times when Black in fact lost the
very slightly worse endgame after a 1.Nf5-Bxf5 2.Bxf5 continuation}) 11. Qf3 $5
{The common move. White wants to double our pawns by Bxf6. Black has three
main options ...c5, ...h6, ...Rb8} (11. Ne2 $6 h6 12. Bh4 (12. Bf4 $2 c5 {
Planning Ba5-Bc7 and c4.} (12... Re8 $15 13. Nd4 Bd7 14. c3 Bf8 15. b4 c5 16.
bxc5 Bxc5 $17 {Generally Black's position TENDS TO BE VERY GOOD ..WHEN WE HAVE
AN ISOLATED PAWN ON d5 AND WHITE HAS A WEAK PAWN ON c3 .LIKE HERE!}) 13. c3 Ba5
