Nc6 3. c3 {the Pontziani opening nothing special about. It is just playable.} (
3. d4 exd4 4. c3 {The Goring gambit or we can call it the boring gambit. It
used to be very popular in the past centuries. When players loved to sacrifice
material for very fast development. Black has many options.} d5 $1 {This is
the official refutation of this system. A typical way to strike against these
gambits.} (4... dxc3 $5 {this is also good objectively, but it plays into
white's hands! ....that is exactly the line the white was aiming for! ...so
lets better avoid it !}) (4... Nf6 $1 5. e5 Nd5 {transposing into the
Pontziani !}) 5. exd5 Qxd5 6. cxd4 {This is the forced established
continuation.} Bg4 7. Nc3 (7. Be2 Bb4+ 8. Nc3 Bxf3 {Transposes into the
mainline.}) 7... Bb4 8. Be2 Bxf3 $1 {Why is this strange looking move good?
The answer is always because my computer says so.} 9. Bxf3 Qc4 10. Bxc6+ {
This move is known for decades.} (10. Qb3 $6 Qxb3 11. axb3 Nge7 12. Be3 O-O-O
13. O-O a5 $36) 10... bxc6 $1 {We want to stop white from castling so it makes
sense to recapture with the pawn.} 11. Qe2+ {This is forced otherwise white's
knight might come under direct threats.} (11. Bd2 Nf6 $36) 11... Qxe2+ 12. Kxe2
O-O-O 13. Be3 Ne7 $1 {Our usual plan is: Ne7-Rhe8-Kb7 and Ba5!-Bb6 to attack
the d4 pawn. Black has a very good position!} 14. Rhd1 (14. Rac1 Ba5 15. Na4
Bb6 16. Rc4 Rd6 17. Rhc1 Re8 18. b4 Nd5 $132) 14... Ba5 {Planning Bb6 to
attack the d4 pawn.} 15. Na4 Bb6 16. Rac1 Rhe8 17. Kf3 Rd6 $36 {Black can go
Rh6/Rg6 next and f5 at the right moment. Black gets a very good practical game.
}) 3... Nf6 $5 {a solid and good approach!} (3... d5 $5 {This is another
playable and good line.} 4. Qa4 {The main continuation} (4. d3 Nf6 {I highly
recommend to not take on e4 to exchange queens. Rather keep the pieces with
Nf6.}) (4. exd5 Qxd5 5. d4 Bg4 6. Be2 O-O-O $15) 4... f6 $1 {Protecting e5.} 5.
d3 Be6 $132) 4. d4 (4. d3 $5 {playing a reversed Phildor !} d5 $1 (4... a5 $5
5. Be2 g6) (4... g6 $5 5. Nbd2 Bg7 6. b4 $1 (6. Be2 a5 $1 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 d6
$36 (8... d5 $36)) 6... d6 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O Nh5 $1 $132) 5. Nbd2 a5 $1 $132 6.
Be2 Bc5 7. O-O O-O) 4... exd4 5. e5 Nd5 6. cxd4 {White usually plays this.} (6.
Qb3 $6 Nb6 7. cxd4 d6 $1 {The best move! We are threatening dxe5 next.} (7...
d5 {this time this does not appear to be working!} 8. Bb5 $1 $14 {White wants
to take on c6, to relieve the pressure from the center.}) (7... Bb4+ $5 8. Bd2
Bxd2+ 9. Nbxd2 d6 $132 10. Bb5 O-O) 8. Bb5 {the only move that has chances to .
.equalize for white!} (8. exd6 Bxd6 9. Bg5 Be7 $15 {Black is better because of
the isolated pawn and there is no attack without the dark-squared bishops if
he exchanges them.}) (8. Ng5 Qe7 $15) 8... Be6 $1 9. Qc2 (9. Qd1 Qd7 10. O-O a6
11. Bxc6 Qxc6 12. Nc3 (12. Ng5 dxe5 13. dxe5 Bd5 $17) 12... Nd5 $15) 9... Qd7 {
Intending ...a6. I very much like Black's position.} 10. O-O (10. Nc3 a6 11.
Bxc6 (11. Be2 $2 dxe5 12. dxe5 Nb4 $19) 11... Qxc6 12. O-O h6 $36 (12... Be7
13. Re1 $14) (12... O-O-O 13. Bg5 Re8 14. Rac1 h6 15. Bf4 Nd5 16. Bg3 Nxc3 17.
Qxc3 Qxc3 18. Rxc3 dxe5 (18... d5) 19. Bxe5 c6 $17) 13. Re1 (13. Rd1 Nd5) (13.
d5 Nxd5 14. Nd4 Nb4 15. Qd2 (15. Qe2 Qc4 16. Nxe6 Qxe6 $17)) 13... Nd5 14. exd6
Bxd6 15. Rxe6+ fxe6 16. Qg6+ Kd7 $1 $15) 10... a6 11. Bxc6 (11. Be2 $2 {
This is not working at all.} dxe5 12. dxe5 Nb4) 11... Qxc6 12. Qxc6+ bxc6 $17
13. Nc3 (13. Ng5 Be7 14. Nxe6 fxe6 15. Nc3 Kd7 16. Bd2 a5 $15) 13... h6 $1 {
Stopping Ng5 and planning Kd7-Nd5.} 14. b3 (14. exd6 cxd6 15. Re1 Kd7 {This is
our time to play for a win now!} 16. Bf4 Nd5 17. Nxd5 Bxd5 {Black can next
plan Be7-Bf6.} 18. Nd2 Be7 19. Be3 Bf6 {One good thing about 1.e4 e5 is that
you are forced to play for a win in slightly better positions. You are forced
to play the endgames with slight edges, this way you improve your endgame
technique and being a better chess player,}) 14... Be7 15. Ba3 a5 16. Rfe1 (16.
Rac1 a4) 16... Kd7 $17 {We are very solid. Next, we can play Nd5.}) (6. Bc4 Nb6
7. Bb3 d5 $1 8. cxd4 (8. exd6 Qxd6 $1 9. O-O (9. cxd4 Be6 $1 10. Nc3 O-O-O 11.
Be3 Bxb3 12. Qxb3 (12. axb3 Qg6 $17 13. O-O Bb4) 12... Qb4 $15) 9... Be6 $1 10.
Bxe6 fxe6 11. Nxd4 Nxd4 12. cxd4 O-O-O 13. Be3 (13. Nc3 Qxd4 $17 14. Qe2 Qc4)
13... Nc4 $132) 8... Bg4 9. Be3 Bb4+ $1 (9... f6 10. O-O Qd7 11. h3 Bh5 12. e6
Qd6 13. Nc3 O-O-O 14. a4 a5 15. Nb5 Qxe6 16. Bf4 Rd7 17. Re1 Qf7 18. Rc1 Bb4
19. Re3 g5 20. Bh2 Nc4 21. Bxc4 dxc4 22. Qc2 Bxf3 23. Rxf3 Nxd4 24. Nxd4 Rxd4
25. Be5 Rd2 26. Qf5+ Qd7 27. Qxf6 Re8 28. Bg3 Rd4 29. Rf1 g4 30. hxg4 Rxg4 31.
Rf4 h5 32. Rxg4 hxg4 33. Rc1 c3 34. bxc3 Bc5 35. Qg5 b6 36. c4 Re4 37. Qg6 Re2
38. Kf1 Qd2 39. Qxg4+ Kb8 40. Qxe2 Qxc1+ 41. Qe1 Qxc4+ 42. Qe2 Qxa4 43. Be5 Bd4
44. Bxd4 Qxd4 45. g4 Qd5 46. Qe8+ Kb7 47. Qa4 b5 48. Qxa5 Qd1+ 49. Qe1 Qxg4 50.
Qe5 Qc4+ 51. Kg2 Qc6+ 52. Kf1 b4 53. f4 b3 54. f5 Ka6 55. Qa1+ Kb6 56. Qh8 Qc1+
57. Kg2 Qc2+ 58. Kh1 b2 59. Qb8+ Ka5 60. Qa7+ Kb4 61. Qb7+ Ka3 62. Qf3+ Qb3 63.
Qa8+ Qa4 64. Qf3+ Ka2 65. Qd5+ Ka1 66. Qe5 c5 {0-1 Hou,Y-Carlsen, M/Wijk aan
Zee 2013/CBM 153}) 10. Nc3 Qd7 11. a3 Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 f6 $36) (6. Bb5 a6 7. Ba4
Nb6 8. Bb3 d5 9. cxd4 Bg4 $36) 6... Bb4+ {The key move. Now White can play 7.
Nbd2 or 7.Bd2 and we have a fine game in both cases.} 7. Nbd2 (7. Bd2 Bxd2+ {
the most simple move with an equal/unclear game!} 8. Nbxd2 (8. Qxd2 d6 9. Bc4
Nb6 10. Bb5 O-O 11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. O-O f6 $1 $132) 8... d6 $1 {We need to
strike fast in the center.} 9. Bb5 (9. Bc4 Be6 {This move is also good enough.}
(9... Nf4 $1 $132 {Also very good according to the computer. White is
overextended in the center without really threatening anything.} 10. O-O O-O
11. Re1 dxe5 12. dxe5 Be6 (12... Bg4 13. Re4) 13. Bxe6 fxe6 $17 {Now there is
pressure along the f-file. Additionally, all the squares on the d-file d4,d3,
and d5 are weak.}) 10. Qb3 (10. exd6 Qxd6 11. O-O O-O-O (11... O-O 12. Ne4 Qb4
13. Qc2 h6 14. Rfe1 Nf4 15. Bxe6 fxe6 (15... Nxe6 16. Nf6+ gxf6 17. Rxe6 fxe6
18. Qg6+ Kh8 $11)) 12. Re1 Rhe8 13. Bb5 Nde7) 10... dxe5 11. dxe5 O-O $36 12.
Qxb7 $4 {White can enter these complications but the resulting positions are
not special for him.} Ndb4 13. Qb5 Rb8 14. Qc5 Nc2+ 15. Ke2 N6d4+ 16. Nxd4
Nxd4+ 17. Kf1 Rxb2 18. Rd1 Rc2 19. Qb4 Nc6 20. Qa4 Bxc4+ 21. Kg1 Rxd2 22. Rc1
Nxe5 23. h4 Qd4 {0-1 Jones,G-Vidit, S/chess.com INT 2018/[,ГйЬннзт]})
9... Bd7 10. Qb3 (10. exd6 cxd6 11. O-O O-O 12. Re1 Rc8 $132) 10... Be6 $1 $11)
7... d6 {If white has a very good center you should challenge it immediately!}
8. Bb5 Nde7 $1 (8... O-O $1 9. O-O dxe5 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. Nxe5 Ne7 $132 {
Even this is about equal. White has slightly better pawn structure but we have
a light-squared bishop.}) 9. O-O dxe5 10. dxe5 O-O 11. h3 $6 (11. a3 Bc5 12. h3
Bf5 $132 {black is standing very well because white has too many weak squares
in the center!}) 11... Bf5 12. Qb3 a6 13. Be2 Be6 $132 *

