{[%evp 0,76,32,20,20,20,20,-32,-45,-48,-7,-32,-6,-16,-16,-14,-14,-16,12,-15,-5,
-38,25,21,-2,-100,-119,-210,-154,-277,-205,-178,-151,-295,-154,-321,-203,-364,
-405,-423,-449,-448,-447,-416,-326,-300,-260,-348,-366,-417,-387,-412,-475,
-510,-426,-435,-435,-437,-437,-451,-461,-471,-461,-472,-487,-486,-482,-480,
-465,-503,-472,-478,-467,-550,-495,-527,-565,-565,-572] This is just a blitz
game. However, an important one.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 Nf6 4. d3 {This is
the reversed philidor defense. Black has several ways to play, for example, 4..
. d5.} g6 {Completely acceptable approach. If White wants to play a slow game,
our bishop fits perfectly on g7.} (4... a5 5. Be2 g6) 5. Nbd2 Bg7 {Black wants
to play a5 to stop b4 next.} (5... a5 6. d4 $1 {White should play d4, if he
plays slow moves he will be worse.} d6 7. Bb5 (7. dxe5 Nxe5 {General rule of
thumb: If your pawn is on g7 recapture on e5 with the pawn. If on g6,
recapture with the knight.} 8. Nxe5 dxe5 9. Bc4)) 6. b4 {The correct move.} (6.
Be2 {If white plays something like than it can be met with} a5 {It is better
to play ...a5 as black then to allow b4 a6.} 7. d4 (7. O-O O-O 8. Nc4 d6 9. a4
h6 {Intending Be6. At some moment black wants to play f7-f5. On the other hand,
white wants to play d3-d4. Black's bishop on g7, is perfectly placed.}) 7... d6
) 6... d6 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O Nh5 9. Re1 Nf4 10. Bf1 f5 11. g3 fxe4 12. dxe4 Nh3+
{In the end black won. The g7-bishop was very important later on.} 13. Kg2 Qf6
14. Re3 g5 15. Bc4+ Kh8 16. Qe2 Ne7 17. Nf1 Ng6 18. Qc2 g4 19. Ne1 Qxf2+ 20.
Qxf2 Rxf2+ 21. Kh1 Bd7 22. Ng2 Raf8 23. Bd2 Bh6 24. a4 Bc6 25. Bd3 Bxe3 26.
Ngxe3 Rxd2 27. Nxd2 Nf2+ 28. Kg1 Nxd3 29. b5 Bd7 30. Nd5 c6 31. bxc6 bxc6 32.
Ne3 Nc5 33. a5 Rb8 34. Rf1 Kg7 35. Rd1 Be6 36. Rf1 d5 37. Nf5+ Bxf5 38. exf5
Nf8 0-1

