1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 Nf6 4. d3 g6 (4... d5 {is also playble which is very
similar to Philidor.} 5. Nbd2 a5 {Securing c5 bishop for our bishop.}) 5. Nbd2
Bg7 6. g3 (6. b4 {White should have played b4.}) 6... O-O 7. Bg2 a5 {Stopping
b4.} 8. O-O d5 {very natural attacking move.} 9. Re1 Re8 10. b3 Bg4 $3 {
This move is anti-positional in most of the cases because white can play h3.
However here it is an exception. Black is threatning d4.} (10... d4 11. cxd4
Nxd4 12. Bb2 {Black is doing very well but white has some counterplay.}) 11. h3
(11. Bb2 Qd7 $3 {Stopping h3 and stabalizing the bishop on g4. We can next
plan a4. Note that ...a4 breaks only work with the queen on d7.} 12. Qc2 Rad8 {
Black is much better.}) 11... Bxf3 12. Qxf3 {White can't recapture with the
knight as it drops the e4 pawn. After dxe4 and trading the queens.} d4 {
Black has a very strong positional advantage.} 13. c4 a4 (13... h5 14. h4 Bh6
$17) 14. Rb1 axb3 15. axb3 Nb4 16. Qe2 (16. Nf1 Qd6 (16... Nd7 17. Bd2) 17. Bd2
Qb6 (17... Nd7 18. c5) 18. Qe2 Nd7 $17) 16... Nd7 17. f4 Nc5 {The position
collapsed very fast for white.} 18. f5 Ncxd3 19. Rf1 Ra2 20. Qd1 Qg5 21. Rf3
Nxc1 0-1

