possible.} (8... O-O 9. Bc4 Nde7 (9... Nb6 10. Bb3 d6 {Its fine to break the
center now as well!}) 10. O-O a6 11. d5 Na5 12. d6 {This is exactly why we
shouldn't delay ...d6 break for too long.}) 9. Bb5 O-O 10. Bxc6 bxc6 {Ideally
in such positions we want our bishop on d5.} 11. O-O Rb8 12. b3 Bf5 13. Rc1 Qd7
14. Nc4 Nb4 (14... Nf4 $15 {Next we are planning Be4-Bd5. As mentioned
previously, we ideally want our bishop on d5.} 15. a3 $2 Be4 16. Ncd2 Bd5 {
The bishop is protecting the c6 pawn, it is being protected and unopposed, and
it is tough for white knights to chase it away}) 15. Qd2 Nd5 16. h3 Be4 17. Qe2
f5 18. Nfd2 Nf4 {This is a blitz game which explains these mistakes.} 19. Qe3
Nxg2 20. Qg3 f4 21. Qg5 h6 22. Qh5 Bd5 23. Kh2 Rf5 24. Qg4 h5 25. Qe2 f3 26.
Qd3 Rf4 27. Rh1 Rh4 28. Kg1 Rxh3 29. Rxh3 Qxh3 30. Nf1 Nf4 0-1

