{The final two lectures of the camp are dedicated to the main line arising
after} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 {The line
starting with 4...Nf6 is the most principled way of playing against the Scotch
Game. Since the arising positions are highly irrational, Black can easily play
for a win. Both sides have so many options that no one can remember all the
possible move orders. Therefore, the lectures are designed to teach the
philosophy of the arising positions. Also, you will learn all the must-know
positional and tactical patterns. At this point, White's main continuation is
6.e5. Of course, all the alternatives are examined as well. All in all, in
this line, Black is doing fine both from theoretical and practical
perspectives. After studying the theoretical files (placed at the beginning),
make sure to check all the model games. After doing this work, you will be
confident enough when facing the Scotch.} *

[Event "MODERN CHESS "]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5.Nxc6 bc6  6.e5  Qe7"]
[Black "FULL THEORY"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[PlyCount "44"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 {AND NOW ...WHITE HAS 4
WAYS OF PLAYING !!! 1) Avoid 6.e5 with moves like 6.Bd3, 6.Nd2, 6.Qe2 etc 2)
Play 6.e5-Qe7 7.Qe2-Nd5 and now deviate from the main line c4 ...with moves
like 8.h4?! 8.g3! , 8.Nd2 etc 3) play 8.c4-Nb6 and now avoid the main line Nc3,
with moves like 9.h4, 9.Nd2, 9.b3, etc 4) play 8.c4-Nb6 9.Nc3 which is the
main line, and I present 2 ways of fighting against it! All are very good with
active counter play but remember: NOONE WITH BLACK OR WITH WHITE CN MEMORIZE
EVERYTHING! ....so practically, even if you don't play the best computer moves,
the game is complicated and very unclear! Giannis Papaioannou} bxc6 6. e5 {
THE MOST AMBITIOUS! ..and the most risky !} (6. Bd3 {playable move of course...
but it doesnt cause any problem} d5 {That is the most simple move and we get a
very nice game easily. White does not put any pressure.} 7. exd5 {This move is
absolutely putting no pressure on us.} (7. e5 $6 {This is almost always a
mistake in the Scotch.} Ng4 {You need to remember a couple of things.} 8. O-O
Bc5 $15 {We are threatening Qh4 and we are even threatening to take the pawn
on e5.} 9. Bf4 (9. Qe2 {This position is theoretically critical because White
is threatening h3.} Qe7 {Threatening the pawn.} 10. Bf4 g5 $3 {Not only in the
Scotch but also in many other 1.e4 e5 openings, you can see this very typical
idea for Black.} 11. Bg3 (11. Bd2 O-O $17 12. e6 Qxe6 13. Qxe6 fxe6) 11... h5 {
Black is better and almost winning by force, for example} 12. h3 h4 $1 $19)
9... f6 $1 10. h3 Nxe5 11. Bxe5 fxe5 12. Qh5+ Kf8 13. Qxe5 Bd6 14. Qe2 g6 15.
Nd2 Kg7 $17) (7. Qe2 dxe4 8. Nd2 $1 (8. Bxe4 $2 Nxe4 9. Qxe4+ Qe7 10. Qxe7+
Bxe7 $17 {it may look strange but black is much better in this endgame!} 11.
Bf4 Rb8 $1 12. b3 Bf6 13. c3 Kd7 $3 14. O-O c5 $3 $15 15. Nd2 Ba6 16. Rfc1 Rhe8
17. Nf3 Kc6 $17)) (7. Nc3 Bb4 {transposes}) (7. Nd2 $2 {again white has mixed
things up and he is just worse with natural moves !} Bd6 $1 8. O-O O-O {
The next move is Re8 and some ideas with Bg4 or even Ng4 at a good moment.} 9.
exd5 cxd5 10. Nf3 h6 $1 $15 11. c4 (11. h3 c5 {and Black has an advantage.} 12.
c4 (12. c3 Be6 {Compared to the previous line, our pieces are very well placed.
(The bishop was on b4)}) 12... d4 $17) 11... dxc4 12. Bxc4 Bb7 $15) 7... cxd5
8. O-O Be7 {Followed by 0-0. We have a good version of the previous chapter
because the bishop is better on e7 than on b4.} 9. c4 (9. Bg5 O-O 10. Nd2 {
Here, Black is a very good game, for example} (10. c4 Rb8 $132) 10... h6 11.
Bh4 Bg4 $1 {I like this move to provoke f3.} 12. f3 Be6 $15 {If given the
