{Black played something else than what I suggest but I am very impressed by
his play.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7 7.
Qe2 Nd5 8. c4 Nb6 9. Nc3 Bb7 10. Bd2 g6 $5 {You may also study this move but
it involves a lot of sacrifices.} 11. Ne4 $6 O-O-O 12. O-O-O (12. a4 {
Threatening a5. But there is this amazing idea:} Qxe5 13. Bc3 {To every human,
this appears to be totally lost. Yet, Black has this move:} Bb4 14. Bxb4 Rhe8
15. f3 d5 $15 {Regaining the piece with a slight advantage.}) (12. Bg5 {
This is totally wrong.} Qxe5 13. Bxd8 Bb4+ 14. Kd1 Rxd8 $19 {This is a
horrible position for White. We are soon going to try to play d5 and give
checkmate.}) 12... c5 $3 $17 {A very accurate move, which I am sure he knew
before the game, and Black is much better.} 13. f4 ({Once again,} 13. Bg5 {
does not work because of} Qxe5 14. Bxd8 Bxe4 {Now there is a huge threat of
Bh6.} 15. Bh4 Bh6+) 13... d6 {Now when the knight is on e4, this c5 move is
very strong.} 14. Bc3 Bh6 {He played all the correct moves.} 15. Nd2 Na4 16.
Ba5 dxe5 17. b3 Nb6 18. fxe5 Rhe8 {In this seriously open position, White is
lacking in development.} 19. Bc3 Nd7 20. Qg4 Qg5 21. Be2 Qe3 22. Kb2 f5 23. Qh4
Bg5 24. Qe1 Nxe5 25. Nf3 Rxd1 26. Qxd1 Bf6 27. Qc2 Be4 28. Qd2 Qxd2+ 29. Nxd2
Bxg2 0-1

