{I recommend that you study games of Almasi in this line.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6
3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7 7. Qe2 Nd5 8. Nd2 (8. c4 Ba6 9.
b3 Qh4 10. a3 Bc5 11. Bb2 Nf4 12. Qf3 Ne6 13. g3 Nd4 $5 14. Qd3 Qg4 15. Nd2 d5
16. Bg2 O-O-O 17. h3 Qh5 18. Bxd4 dxc4 19. Nxc4 Rxd4 20. Nd6+ Kb8 21. Qxa6
Qxe5+ {=/+/-/+ Handoko-Xie Jun/Jakarta/1994/}) 8... g6 9. c4 Ba6 {Maybe that
was preparation of that time.} (9... Nf4 $15 {is the best move here.} 10. Qe4
Ne6) 10. Qe4 (10. Ne4 Qb4+ (10... Bg7 11. Bg5 Qxe5 12. Nc5 $13) 11. Nd2 Bg7 $15
) 10... f5 {Another typical move even though it is a bit rare.} 11. Qd4 $6 (11.
exf6 $142 Nxf6 12. Qxe7+ Bxe7 {was possibly best for White. At some point,
Black has to do something with the Ba6. Either play d5 and exchange it or play
Bb7 and c5. White has the better pawn structure, so if Black does not play
energetically, we might end up worse.}) 11... Nb4 12. Qc3 c5 $1 {Black simply
protected everything. If he manages to develop his pieces and castle, he is
winning.} 13. Be2 (13. Nf3 $142 Bg7 14. Bg5 Qe6 15. Be2 Bb7 $15) 13... Bg7 14.
f4 $2 {A bad move.} (14. Nf3) 14... d6 (14... Bb7 15. Bf3 $1) 15. Nf3 (15. a3
Nc6 16. Bf3 Bb7 17. Qb3 O-O-O 18. Qa4 (18. Qb5 a6 19. Qa4 Nd4 $17) 18... Qe8
$17) 15... Bb7 $17 {Think about this position as an open chess position with
attacking possibilities.} 16. a3 Nc6 {and later he won the game.} 17. Qb3 Rb8
18. exd6 cxd6 19. Qe3 (19. O-O $4 Nd4 20. Nxd4 Bxd4+ 21. Kh1 Bxg2+ $19) 19...
Nd4 (19... Qxe3 20. Bxe3 Bxb2 21. Ra2 Bc3+ 22. Bd2 {-/+/-+ K}) 20. Qxe7+ Kxe7
21. Kf2 Be4 $5 {/\Nb3,Rhe8} (21... Bxf3 22. Bxf3 Nxf3 23. Kxf3 Rb3+ $1 $19) 22.
Ra2 (22. Nd2 Nb3 23. Nxb3 Rxb3 {/\Rhb8,Bd4-+}) 22... Nxe2 23. Kxe2 Rhe8 24. Kf2
Rb3 25. h4 (25. Re1 $142) 25... Bxf3 26. gxf3 Bd4+ $19 {K} 27. Kg3 Kf7 28. Rd1
Re2 29. Bd2 Bf2+ 30. Kh3 Rxf3+ 31. Kg2 Rd3 0-1

