1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. Bd3 d5 {White needs
to be very careful here because 7.e5, 7.Nd2, and 7.Qe2 are mistakes, and only
7.exd5 is playable.} 7. Qe2 dxe4 8. Bxe4 $6 Nxe4 9. Qxe4+ Qe7 10. Qxe7+ Bxe7 {
In this endgame, Black, surprisingly, has quite a big advantage. The c-pawns
are not particularly weak because they are on a closed file.} 11. O-O (11. Bf4
Rb8 (11... Bf6 12. c3 Kd7 ({First we add} 12... Rb8 13. b3 {and then} Kd7 {
An amazing move. The idea is to bring the king to c6.} 14. O-O c5 15. Rc1 Kc6 {
Everything is protected and our king is quite safe. Black is playing for a win.
})) 12. b3 {Black can protect the pawn with Rb7 but 11...Bf6 is an even more
amazing idea here.}) 11... Bf5 12. c3 O-O ({I would have castled long just to
keep c7 safe.} 12... O-O-O) 13. Bf4 Rfb8 14. b3 Bf6 {He played for
compensation.} 15. Bxc7 Re8 16. Bf4 {Of course, we do not want to take on b1
and take the pawn on c3. This would be a horrible mistake.} Re2 ({Maybe even} 
16... g5 {if it was not for Be3.} 17. Bg3 h5 18. h3 h4 19. Bh2 Rad8) 17. Be3 h5
{Very good move potentially intending to play g5 and Kh7.} 18. Rd1 Bc2 19. Rc1
Re8 20. Na3 R8xe3 21. Nxc2 Rxc3 22. Ne3 Rxa2 23. Rxa2 Rxc1+ 24. Nf1 Bd4 25. g3
Rb1 26. Rd2 c5 27. Rd3 f5 28. Kg2 Kf7 29. Rf3 Ke6 30. Nd2 Re1 31. Nc4 g5 32. h3
Re2 33. g4 hxg4 34. hxg4 f4 {And later he won the game.} 35. Kf1 Rc2 36. Ke1
Kd5 37. Kf1 Ra2 38. Kg1 Ra1+ 39. Kg2 Ra2 40. Kg1 a5 41. Kg2 a4 42. Nb6+ Kc6 43.
Nxa4 c4 44. Nc3 cxb3 0-1

