1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. Nd2 {This is
already a bit suspicious.} d5 {Here, White should take on d5 followed by a
fast Bb5+ in order to get an equal game.} 7. Bd3 {This is a surprising mistake.
} Bd6 8. O-O O-O 9. h3 Re8 10. exd5 {White needs to take as he cannot move his
knight from d2 and develop his pieces.} cxd5 11. Nf3 h6 {We can also play c5.}
12. c3 Ne4 (12... c5 {Black would like to exchange dark-squared bishops, not
light-squared bishops.} 13. Bb5 Re7 {After Bd7 we would have a good position
but we can also get ambitious.}) 13. Re1 Bb7 14. Nd4 Qf6 {With a fine attack.}
15. Bxe4 dxe4 16. Nb5 Be5 17. Be3 a6 {Black is better.} 18. Nd4 Bd6 19. Ne2 Qh4
20. Qa4 Qf6 21. c4 Bc6 22. Qc2 Be5 23. Nc3 Qe6 24. b3 f5 25. Rad1 Rad8 {
Black is not at all afraid to open up the position as the bishops are
extremely strong.} 26. Ne2 Qf6 27. Nf4 g5 28. Nd5 Qe6 29. Nb4 Bb7 30. Rxd8 Rxd8
31. Rd1 Rxd1+ 32. Qxd1 Qd6 33. Qxd6 cxd6 34. Nc2 Kf7 35. Bd4 Ke6 36. Bxe5 Kxe5
{Even this endgame is better for Black.} 37. g3 f4 38. g4 a5 39. Kf1 d5 40.
cxd5 Ba6+ 41. Ke1 Kxd5 42. Kd2 Bf1 43. f3 exf3 44. b4 0-1

